my:Hazard.my:ControlMeasures:
a) Primary and back up communication should be agreed between concerned ships; 
b) All communication should be performed in English; 
c) Radio check to be carried out prior operations commencing and at regular intervals thereafter.

a) Larger vessel in normal circumstances would act as mother vessel, anchored; 
b) Ensure sufficient number of proper size fenders are put in place; 
c) Approach to mother ship to be performed according to good seaman ship practice taking into account weather, tidal, surface currents, etc. conditions; 
d) Ensure adequate lighting is available during hours of darkness; 
e) All crew to be briefed before the operation.

a) Both ships to be positioned in such a way that their bridge wings, cranes or any other part of their ships wouldn’t make contact due to motion of the ship operating her cargo cranes, due to swell, other ships passing nearby, etc.; 
b) Ensure sufficient number of proper size fenders are put in place; 
c) Ensure both vessels are kept upright taking into account ballast operation and cargo distribution; 
d) Local weather forecast should be monitored; 
e) Agree on contingency plan in case the weather deteriorates considerably e.g. suspending of the operation, cast off, etc.; 
f) Deck watch maintained paying particular attention to mooring ropes; 
g) Adequate lighting provided; 
h) Consider if repositioning of the fenders is necessary (e.g. due to draft changes) to avoid damage to e.g. ships railings; 
i) All crew to be briefed prior to operation.

a) Means of personnel transfer between ships to be agreed and arranged accordingly, either using pilot ladder, portable gangway or accommodation ladder; 
b) Safety net to be attached in such a way that the whole area between ships is protected; 
c) Standing on fenders should be avoided; 
d) The mean of access should be monitored taking into account that both vessels’ free board will change during the operation; 
e) Refer also to ‘Rigging/Stowing Accommodation Ladder/Portable Gangway’ Risk Assessment.

a) Ensure in the anchorage there is sufficient depth taking account of tides, ship's swinging on tidal stream(s) or on the wind; 
b) Anchor watch on the bridge to be maintained; 
c) Consider if anchoring on both anchors would be necessary (to be agreed with mother ship in advance).
